<p><span style="font-size: 36px;">M</span>onitoring Crypto markets day in and day out is a tedious task, so I came up with an idea to create a bot using <span style="background-color: rgb(209, 213, 216);"><strong>Node JS and Express</strong></span>, which does all the scanning/monitoring for me and notifies me via Twitter when whatever condition I have specified is met.</p>

<p>The bot has its own private <span style="background-color: rgb(209, 213, 216);"><strong>Twitter</strong></span> account, and we follow the bot&#39;s twitter account and have push notifications enabled to get notified about the market immediately&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;<span class="fr-img-caption fr-fic fr-dib" style="width: 163px;"><span class="fr-img-wrap"><img src="blob:http://localhost:3000/0e051deb-0b9e-459b-8d03-228f192c574d" alt="Crypto Bot with Twitter"><span class="fr-inner">This is our Crypto Bot</span></span>&nbsp;</span>
</p>

<p>So, lets get started !!</p>

<p>You will need the tool/s mentioned below.</p>

<p style="margin-left: 20px;"><span style="font-size: 24px;">Node.js</span></p>

<p>
	<br>
</p>

<p>Install <span style="background-color: rgb(209, 213, 216);"><strong>Node.js</strong></span> and <span style="background-color: rgb(209, 213, 216);"><strong>NPM</strong></span> will get installed along with it.</p>

<p>Get you project setup by using</p>

<p class="srcCode" data="npm init" type="bash">npm init</p>

<p>Next, we have to install a few npm packages like <span style="background-color: rgb(209, 213, 216);"><strong>twitter and ws</strong></span> (websocket)</p>

<p class="srcCode" data="npm install --save twitter ws" type="bash">npm install --save twitter ws</p>

<p>Install <strong><span style="background-color: rgb(209, 213, 216);">nodemon</span></strong> globally using&nbsp;</p>

<p class="srcCode" data="npm install --g nodemon" type="bash">npm install --g nodemon</p>

<p>Open this project in any code editor like VS Code, Atom etc. I personally like VS Code.</p>

<p>The project should look something like this.</p>

<p><span class="fr-img-caption fr-fic fr-dib" style="width: 654px; width: 654px;"><span class="fr-img-wrap"><img src="blob:http://localhost:3000/c8ffba72-8fe3-4602-b849-dbe3b0a6a402" alt="Initial Project Setup"><span class="fr-inner">Initial Project Setup</span></span>&nbsp;</span>
</p>

<p><span class="fr-img-caption fr-fic fr-dib fr-draggable" contenteditable="false" draggable="false" style="width: 654px; width: 654px;">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p>then create a twitter developer account and on <a href="https://apps.twitter.com"><strong>apps.twitter.com</strong></a></p>

<p>Generate <strong><span style="background-color: rgb(209, 213, 216);">access token and secret</span></strong> for the Twitter app.</p>

<p>Now, create a file called <strong><span style="background-color: rgb(209, 213, 216);">server.js</span></strong>, it should look somewhat like this.</p>

<p class="srcCode" data="// server.js
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');
const ws = require('ws');
//Twitter API Keys
const Twitter = require('twitter');
var client = new Twitter({
  consumer_key: '2FuxLkb9v1Y7tHm75YAC8B8s0',
